ts of his memory were reinforced, others were erased. Emphasizing the constant and diverse nature of this negotiation, this book proposes a nuanced interpretation of both the Flavian age itself and its relation to Nero's Rome. By combining the study of these strategies with architectural approaches, archaeology, and memory studies, this volume offers a multifaceted picture of Roman civilization at a crucial turning point, and as such will have something to offer anyone interested in classics, (ancient) history, and archaeology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aAncient history. 4aAntiquity. 4aArchaeology by period / region. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aHistorical and cultural areas within Italy. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aImperial Rome, Flavian dynasty, classics, ancient history.1 aAmbühl, Annemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCominesi, Aurora Raimondi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordes, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallia, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeerink, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeerink, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeijer, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeijer, Esther, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoormann, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNauta, Ruurd, econtrib